<p>you can also provide a full path to your mpi</p><p>#/usr/lib/openmpi/1.2.5-gcc/bin/mpiexec -n 2 ./a.out</p><p></p><p></p><div><span class="gmail_quote">On 8/12/08, <b class="gmail_sendername">jody</b> &lt;<a href="mailto:jody.xha@gmail.com">jody.xha@gmail.com</a>&gt; wrote:</span><blockquote class="gmail_quote" style="margin:0;margin-left:0.8ex;border-left:1px #ccc solid;padding-left:1ex">
No.<br> The PATH variable simply tells the system in which order the<br> directories should be searched for executables.<br> <br> so in .bash_profile just add the line<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;PATH=/usr/lib/openmpi/1.2.5-gcc/bin:$PATH<br> after the line<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;PATH=$PATH:$HOME/bin<br> <br> Then the system will search in /usr/lib/openmpi/1.2.5-gcc/bin before<br> it will look<br> in the directories it would have looked in anyway.<br> <br><br> <br> Jody<br> <br><br> On Tue, Aug 12, 2008 at 11:59 AM, Rayne &lt;<a href="mailto:lancer6238@yahoo.com">lancer6238@yahoo.com</a>&gt; wrote:<br>
 &gt; My .bash_profile and .bashrc on the server are exactly the same as that on my PC. However, I can run mpiexec without any problems just using my PC as a single node, i.e. without trying to login to other servers and using multiple nodes. I only get the errors on the server.<br>
 &gt;<br> &gt; In .bash_profile, I see<br> &gt;<br> &gt; PATH=$PATH:$HOME/bin<br> &gt;<br> &gt; If I change this, won&#39;t it affect other programs as well?<br> &gt;<br> &gt; Thank you.<br> &gt;<br> &gt; Regards,<br> &gt; Rayne<br>
